5. yeneris ‹ze-familiae] The gens of the Tuberones was the Aelia, which contained the Paeti, the Lamiae, and other families. One of the Paeti named Sextus Aelius, consul 13.c. 198, was a jurisconsult‚ and also his brother Publius. In the family of the Tuberones, Q. Aelius Tubero, called the Stoic, was praetor 13.c. l23; he had some reputation as a lawyer and was an honest man (Pro Murena, c. 36). L. Aelius Tu- bero, the father of the man whom Cicero is addressing, was an historical writer and a philosopher. His son was the jurist Q. Tu- bero, who is often cited in the Digest.
